{{Infobox book | name = Thinking Strategically: The Competitive Edge in Business, Politics, and Everyday Life | title_orig = | translator = | image = Thinking Strategically - bookcover.jpg | border = | caption = Softcover edition | author = [[Avinash Dixit]], [[Barry Nalebuff]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | subject = [[Strategy]], [[game theory]], decision making | genre = Non-fiction | publisher = [[W. W. Norton & Company]] | release_date = February 1, 1991 | english_release_date = | media_type = Print, e-book | pages = 393 pp. | isbn = 978-0393029239 | dewey = | congress = | oclc = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Thinking Strategically: The Competitive Edge in Business, Politics, and Everyday Life''''' is a non-fiction book by Indian-American economist [[Avinash Dixit]] and [[Barry Nalebuff]], a professor of economics and management at [[Yale School of Management]]. The text was initially published by [[W. W. Norton & Company]] on February 1, 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/0393029239|publisher=[[amazon.com]]|title=Thinking Strategically: The Competitive Edge in Business, Politics, and Everyday Life|accessdate=2015-05-06}}</ref>
==Overview== The book discusses issues of strategic behaviour, decision making, and [[game theory]]. The authors present the main concepts, such as [[backward induction]], [[auction theory]], [[Nash equilibrium]], noncooperative bargaining, to a general audience. Each concept is illustrated by examples from common life, business, sports, politics, etc.—as applying game theory to real life may be the best way of crystallizing the best options available.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/2138835?uid=3738936&uid=2&uid=4&sid=21106298406241|publisher=[[jstor.org]]|title=Thinking Strategically: The Competitive Edge in Business, Politics, and Everyday Life|accessdate=2015-05-06}}</ref>
==Reception== {{quote|Today our writers and critics nominate the books they have enjoyed reading most over the last twelve months. No rules were imposed but, as you will see, all have been encouraged to be adventurous and broaden their interests away from their usual subjects
''Thinking Strategically'' by Avinash Dixit & Barry Nalebuff (W W Norton) offers essential training in making choices and weighing possibilities not only in business but in daily life. Reading it is a trip to the gym for the reasoning faculties. It presents game theory and business strategy as understandable, usable and everyday tools for living with others. Its examples of tactics in action range from King Lear to Maradonna. And the case studies make great bit-reading in queues or waiting-rooms. I also much enjoyed Howard Rheingold's ''Virtual Reality'' (Secker & Warburg), which describes the computer-created world waiting around the corner of the century, and Simon Schama's ''Dead Certainties'' (Granta), which sent a bright spark between history and fiction: illuminating.}}
—Review by ''Financial Times''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artofstrategy.net/thinkingstrategically.html|publisher=artofstrategy.net|title=Here are the reviews for our first book, ''Thinking Strategically''|accessdate=2015-05-06|first=Andrew |last=St. George|date=December 7, 1991}}</ref>
